newsitem.title: USA: CBOT wheat closes lower on weather, soybean drop.
newsitem.headline: CBOT wheat closes lower on weather, soybean drop.

text.p: Improved weather for seeding the U.S. winter wheat crop and another sharp drop in soybeans drove CBOT wheat futures to a lower close, traders said.
"It was more fund liquidation," said Ron Kucha of O'Connor and Co. "Funds usually liquidate for two or three days in a row so we'll see what tomorrow brings."
Weather forecasts for the U.S. Midwest indicated conditions more conducive for seeding the 1997 U.S. winter wheat crop.
Traders said wheat futures were recently boosted into near neutral territory on daily charts.
The nine-day relative strength index (RSI) had dropped to 23.7 on September 17 and Tuesday had moved back to 50.842.
Technicians generally view an RSI of 20 or less as indicative of an oversold market while a level of 80 or more is considered an overbought market.
The 14 day RSI Tuesday was at 46.063 and the December contract closed above its 18 day moving average (MA) of $4.30-7/8 and below the 40 day MA at $4.46-3/4.
Wheat closed one to 3-3/4 cents per bushel lower, with December down 2-1/4 at $4.33-3/4. March was 3-3/4 lower at $4.18-3/4.
Wheat futures volume was estimated at 19,000 contracts, down slightly from 19,873 Monday, according to the CBOT.
In wheat options, Refco Inc sold 350 December $4.50 calls at 8-1/2, the traders said. Continental Grain bought 250 March $4.20 calls and sold 250 March $4.60 calls at 13-3/4 cents.
Wheat options volume was estimated at 5,000 contracts, down from 5,620 Monday.
